      "writtenOn": "2020-08-28T04:44:38Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "fairly certain this is incorrect\n\nenvp is a pointer to a pointer to an array of pointers.  it\u0027s stored on the stack, so it\u0027s always valid.\n\n*envp is a pointer to an array of pointers which needs to be NULL terminated.  it starts off NULL.  you allocated a single entry above.\n\n(*envp)[0] is a pointer to a string.  \u0027\\0\u0027 is a character, not a pointer.  it happens to work out to be 0 which is the same \"value\" as NULL, but it\u0027s not the same at the language level.  you need to assign NULL here.\n\nor you could simply use calloc() which zeros the memory for you.",
      "revId": "106818f2323dba924880177ed86bcd40de42cc15",
